# Fluff Date: 2026-02-26 19:50:04
<overview>
<p>In 3031, Ceres Metals Industries released the Chariot High-Speed Medevac, a Capellan-produced derivative of the Wangker AeroSpace C-790 Protector. A number of Protectors had been captured by Capellan forces during the Fourth Succession War, and Ceres wasted little time in reverse-engineering the aircraft for domestic production. The Chariot was intended to fill the Confederation's desperate need for high-speed medical evacuation aircraft, a capability that had been sorely lacking during the devastating Fourth War. Rather than produce a direct copy, however, Ceres made deliberate modifications that reflected the Confederation's own military medical doctrine and the harsh realities of its limited trained personnel.</p>
</overview>

<capabilities>
<p>The Chariot retains the Protector's proven airframe and high-speed performance, including its Mach 3 burst capability and STOL operations through vectored-thrust wing-mounted engines. Where the Chariot differs significantly is in its medical configuration. Rather than replicating the Protector's ten individual paramedic stations, Ceres Metals replaced the paramedic bays with a single-theater MASH module. While the Chariot carries a ton less armor protection than the Protector, this trade-off provides a substantially higher level of care for its patients. The MASH module allows onboard surgical capability, meaning that critically wounded soldiers can receive definitive treatment during transit rather than merely stabilization.</p><p>The reduced armor is a calculated risk. Ceres engineers reasoned that a medevac aircraft operating in the rear areas of an engagement zone faces less direct fire than front-line combat craft, and that the weight savings were better spent on medical equipment that would save more lives than an additional ton of plating.</p>
</capabilities>

<deployment>
<p>The Chariot serves primarily with CCAF medical units and Capellan planetary garrisons, where it provides rapid casualty evacuation from forward engagement zones. The aircraft has also found buyers among Capellan-allied mercenary commands and the Confederation's Trinity alliance partners. The Chariot's MASH module makes it particularly valuable in theaters where ground-based hospitals are distant or unavailable, allowing surgical teams to operate while the aircraft is in flight.</p>
</deployment>

<history>
<p>Wangker AeroSpace lodged a formal complaint with the reconstituted Star League regarding Ceres Metals' unlicensed production of the Chariot, charging the Capellan firm with blatant design theft. The legal proceedings dragged on inconclusively before the fall of the Star League ended any hope of adjudication. Ceres Metals has never acknowledged the charge, maintaining that the Chariot is an independent design that merely shares a similar performance profile with the Protector.</p><p>Regardless of its legal origins, the Chariot proved to be an effective medical platform. The decision to substitute a MASH module for the Protector's paramedic stations reflected the harsh realities of Capellan military medicine -- with fewer trained paramedics available than the Federated Suns could field, concentrating surgical capability into a single module made better use of the Confederation's limited medical personnel. The Chariot has remained in steady production at Ceres facilities since 3031, filling a critical support role in the CCAF's force structure that no other Capellan aircraft can match.</p>
</history>

